					<head>Commentary</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85013597" rend="visible">
						<summary>A commentary on the Song of Songs by Yohanan Allemanno.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85013597">
							<locus from="1r" to="365v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Ḥesheḳ Shelomoh : Perush shir ha-shirim</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">חשק שלמה : פרוש שיר השירים </title>
							<author key="http://viaf.org/viaf/24763579">
								<persName key="http://viaf.org/viaf/24763579" xml:lang="he">אלמנו, יוחנן בן יצחק</persName>
								<persName key="http://viaf.org/viaf/24763579" xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Allemanno, Yohanan, approximately 1435-approximately 1504 </persName>
							</author>
							<colophon xml:lang="he">נשלם זה הספר נקרא חשק שלמה ע"י אני הוא הצעיר ממשפחתו <name type="person" role="scribe"> יעקב בכמ"ר מרדכי פוייטי</name>ינש ק'  <date when="1578" calendar="Hebrew">פיבראר של"ח" לפ"ק</date> למען רחמיך הרבים וחסדיך הגדולים יזכני להגות בו ובשאר ספרי הקדש אני וזרעי וזרע זרעו כמו שכתוב לא ומושו מפיך ומפי זרעך ומפי זרע זרעך אמר לי מעתה ועד עולם. והחוט המשולש לא במהרה ינתק וכן יהי רצון ונאמן אמן. כי לאוא"ס.   <locus n="365v"/>
							</colophon>
							<note>
								<p>In the introduction the author refers to his patrons, Lorenzo di Medici (folio 1v) and Giovanni Pico della Mirandola (folio 2v), on request of whom the commentary was written in 1489.</p>
							</note>
							<filiation>Cf. Allemanno's other treatises, <ref target="Neubauer_1891" type="number">1535</ref> and <ref target="Steinschneider_1879" type="number">143</ref>.</filiation>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Paper codex, Italian cursive script, unpunctuated, of 16th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="chart">
								<support>Paper codex.</support>
								<extent rend="visible">372 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>210</height>
										<width>160</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>163</height>
										<width>100</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>372 folios (+ 3 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and 4 at the end; there are also 12 blank leaves after the last written folio).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Quires of mostly 10 leaves each.</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout ruledLines="34" writtenLines="34" columns="1">
									<p>Has several marginal notes.</p>
									<p>Watermarks of a serpent, similar to Briquet no. 13680, dated Milano 1590, see <ref target="Briquet_1968" type="page">679</ref>, volume 4.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Italian cursive script, unpunctuated, of 16th century. <name type="person" role="scribe">Ya῾aḳov ben Mordekhai Foetti</name>: inscribed in the colophon, folio 365v.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="sole"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Folios <locus from="366r" to="372v"/> - smaller (octavo) leaves, containing quotations from Ḥesheḳ Shelomoh, with references to the pages of the manuscript. This part was probably added in the 17th century.</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="censor">Boniforte Assinar</name>, inscribed with his name, folio 365v.</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="censor">Hieron Carolus</name>, inscribed with his name and a date of <date calendar="Gregorian">1582</date>, folio 365v.</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600; red and brown gold-tooled leather.</p>
								<p>Spine: 'Heshek Shelomoh. Hebrew. Brit. Mus. Oriental Ms. 2854.'</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
